T1  - Some personal reflections on Michael Banton's illustrious career in the sociology of race relations
AN  - 2164082771
AB  - Given that we already have two excellent appreciations of Michael's overall contributions to the field of race and ethnic relations, as well as to sociological theory and social policy more broadly (Barot 2006; Husbands 2016), I have decided to confine my reflections to a couple of areas where my friendship with Michael has been particularly rewarding for me and to other activities in which we have both been involved. As my career has been split between Britain and America, and increasingly in the latter country in recent years, it is to this earlier period that I will focus my comments. Let me say at the outset of these remarks that I did not always agree with Michael's intellectual positions on a variety of issues. But this was never a problem with Michael whose philosophy was to challenge ideas with other ideas and that such a procedure was the only manner in which academic progress would ever take place. The Ghost of Karl Popper loomed large in his weltanschauung which was indeed fortunate as on several issues I found myself agreeing with his great rival John Rex, who was a little less comfortable with intellectual dissent! Michael himself never failed to explore a vast range of topics — from ideas concerning racial theories, case studies of race relations in West Africa and Britain, not to mention both national and global reports on such practical issues like policing and the intemational action against racial discrimination — and he was even prepared to continue his debates with John Rex's positions even after John's death in December 2011 (Symposium 2015). So I am sure that he would have no objection to me taking issue with some of his own arguments at a time when he is no longer able to respond in person. 
